{"title_page": "Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n| image_skyline                   = Isto\u010dno Sarajevo, kostel.jpg\n| imagesize                       = 255px\n| image_caption                   = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea\n| settlement_type                 = [[Municipalities of Republika Srpska|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Entity]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Republika Srpska]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina|City]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]]\n| timezone                        = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset                      = +1\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +2\n| unit_pref                       = \n| map_caption                     = Location of Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea within Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| name                            = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea\n| native_name                     = \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430\n| official_name                   = \n| other_name                      = East Ilid\u017ea\n| image_shield                    = \n| image_map                       = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea municipality.svg\n| mapsize                         = 175px\n| area_blank1_title               = Town\n| area_blank1_km2                 = \n| area_blank2_title               = Municipality\n| area_blank2_km2                 = 27.9\n| population_as_of                = 2013 census\n| population_blank1_title         = Town\n| population_blank1               = 14241\n| population_density_blank1_km2   = auto\n| population_blank2_title         = Municipality\n| population_blank2               = 14763\n| population_density_blank2_km2   = auto|latd\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|44|15|N|18|41|E|source:kolossus-srwiki|display=inline, title}}\n| area_code                       = 57\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = |\n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Marinko Bo\u017eovi\u0107 ([[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|SDS]]) [http://www.izbori.ba/documents/Rezultati%20izbora%202004/Utvrdjeni/2004NacelniciRS.pdf]\n| leader_party                    = ||\n| image_map1                      = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea-naselja.PNG\n}}\n'''Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430}}, \"East Ilid\u017ea\") is a municipality in the city of [[Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]] located in [[Republika Srpska]], an entity of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. As of 2013, it has a population of 14,763 inhabitants.\n\nIt was also known as '''''Srpska Ilid\u017ea''''' (\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430, \"Serbian Ilid\u017ea\"), as well as [[Kasindo]], and was created from part of the pre-war municipality of [[Ilid\u017ea]] (the other part of the pre-war municipality is now in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]). There have been some proposals for the municipality to be merged with that of [[Isto\u010dno Novo Sarajevo (Republika Srpska)|Isto\u010dno Novo Sarajevo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.glassrpske.com/latn/?page=&kat=&vijest=9264 |title=Glas Srpske |access-date=2006-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927012257/http://www.glassrpske.com/latn/?page=&kat=&vijest=9264 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n=== Population ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Population of settlements \u2013 Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea municipality\n|-\n|\n|Settlement\n|1991.\n|2013.\n|-\n|\n|Total\n|16,754\n|14,763\n|-\n|1\n|Kasindo\n|911\n|539\n|-\n|2\n|Krupac\n|\n|232\n|}\n\n=== Ethnic composition ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Ethnic composition \u2013 Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea municipality\n|-\n|\n|2013.\n|-\n|Total\n|14.763 (100,0%)\n|-\n|Serbs\n|13.755 (93,17%)\n|-\n|Bosniaks\n|648 (4,389%)\n|-\n|Others\n|204 (1,382%)\n|-\n|Croats\n|156 (1,057%)\n|}\n\n==Sport==\nThe local [[Football team|football club]] is [[FK Famos Vojkovi\u0107i|FK Famos]], which competes in the First League of the [[Republika Srpska]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081208080139/http://www.istocnailidza.net/index.php Official website]\n\n{{Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Istocna Ilidza}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]]\n\n{{Isto\u010dnaIlid\u017ea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|image_skyline = Isto\u010dno Sarajevo, kostel.jpg\n|imagesize              = 255px\n|image_caption          = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea\n|settlement_type = [[Municipalities of Republika Srpska|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Entity]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Republika Srpska]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[List of cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina|City]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]]\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST = +2\n|unit_pref=\n|map_caption =Location of Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea within Bosnia and Herzegovina\n|name = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea\n|native_name = \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430\n|official_name = \n|other_name = East Ilid\u017ea\n|image_shield = \n|image_map = Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea municipality.svg\n|mapsize   = 175px\n| area_blank1_title = Town\n| area_blank1_km2   = \n| area_blank2_title = Municipality\n| area_blank2_km2   = 27.9\n| population_as_of  = 2013 census\n| population_blank1_title = Town\n| population_blank1 = 14241\n| population_density_blank1_km2 = auto\n| population_blank2_title = Municipality\n| population_blank2 = 14763\n| population_density_blank2_km2 = auto\n|latd\n|coordinates            = {{coord|44|15|N|18|41|E|source:kolossus-srwiki|display=inline, title}}\n|area_code = 57\n|website = \n|footnotes = \n||leader_title=[[Mayor]]|\nleader_name = Marinko Bo\u017eovi\u0107 ([[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|SDS]]) [http://www.izbori.ba/documents/Rezultati%20izbora%202004/Utvrdjeni/2004NacelniciRS.pdf]\n|leader_party = \n| \n|}}\n'''Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430}}, \"East Ilid\u017ea\") is a municipality in the city of [[Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]] located in [[Republika Srpska]], an entity of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. As of 2013, it has a population of 14,763 inhabitants.\n\nIt was also known as '''''Srpska Ilid\u017ea''''' (\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u045f\u0430, \"Serbian Ilid\u017ea\"), as well as [[Kasindo]], and was created from part of the pre-war municipality of [[Ilid\u017ea]] (the other part of the pre-war municipality is now in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]). There have been some proposals for the municipality to be merged with that of [[Isto\u010dno Novo Sarajevo (Republika Srpska)|Isto\u010dno Novo Sarajevo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.glassrpske.com/latn/?page=&kat=&vijest=9264 |title=Glas Srpske |access-date=2006-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927012257/http://www.glassrpske.com/latn/?page=&kat=&vijest=9264 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the census of 2013, the population of the municipality was 14,763.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popis.gov.ba/popis2013/doc/RezultatiPopisa_BS.pdf|title=Census of Population, Households and Dwellings in Bosnia and Herzegovina: Final results|publisher=Agency for Statistics of Bosnia and Herzegovina|date=June 2016|page=37|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 Census  ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Municipality\n! colspan=\"6\" | Nationality\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{center|Total}}\n|-\n! {{center|Bosniaks}}\n! {{center|%}}\n! {{center|Croats}}\n! {{center|%}}\n! {{center|Serbs}}\n! {{center|%}}\n|-\n| Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea\n| {{right|648}} || {{right|4.38}}\n| {{right|156}}  || {{right|1.05}}\n| {{right|13755 }}  || {{right|93.17}}\n| {{right|14,763}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sport==\nThe local [[Football team|football club]] is [[FK Famos Vojkovi\u0107i|FK Famos]], which competes in the First League of the [[Republika Srpska]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081208080139/http://www.istocnailidza.net/index.php Official website]\n\n{{Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Istocna Ilidza}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Isto\u010dna Ilid\u017ea]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Isto\u010dno Sarajevo]]\n\n{{Isto\u010dnaIlid\u017ea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "EcLiPsE285", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isto%C4%8Dna_Ilid%C5%BEa"}
{"title_page": "Er\u00e9ndira (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1983 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Er\u00e9ndira\n| image          = Erendira.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ruy Guerra]]\n| producer       = Alain Queff\u00e9l\u00e9an<br>Regina Ziegler\n| writer         = [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n| starring       = [[Irene Papas]]<br>[[Cl\u00e1udia Ohana]]<br>Oliver Wehe<br>[[Michael Lonsdale]]\n| music          = Maurice Lecoeur\n| cinematography = [[Denys Clerval]]\n| editing        = Kenout Peltier\n| studio         = [[Les Films du Triangle]]<br>[[Films A2]]<br>[[Cin\u00e9 Qua Non]]<br>[[Atlas Saskia Film]]<br>[[Austra]]\n| distributor    = [[Miramax]]\n| released       = {{film date|1983|9|12|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = Mexico<br>France<br>West Germany\n| language       = Spanish\n}}\n\n'''''Er\u00e9ndira''''' is a 1983 [[drama film]] directed by [[Ruy Guerra]]. The film script was written by [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]. The original script actually preceded his [[novella]] ''[[The Incredible and Sad Tale of Innocent Er\u00e9ndira and Her Heartless Grandmother]]'' published in 1972.<ref name = \"Garc\u00eda Saucedo 93\">Warwick, ''Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine'', p. 93</ref> The characters of Er\u00e9ndira and her grandmother had already appeared briefly in his book ''[[One Hundred Years of Solitude]]'' (1967). Garcia Marquez' recreated the screenplay from memory (the original was lost) for Guerra's film.<ref>{{cite news\n | last =Canby\n | first = Vincent\n | title = ERENDIRA : A GIRL, A GRANDMOTHER AND A LIBERATOR\n | work =[[The New York Times]] \n | date = 1 October 1983\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1983/10/01/movies/erendira-a-girl-a-grandmother-and-a-liberator.html\n | accessdate = 14 July 2013 }}</ref> Guerra incorporated elements from another Garcia Marquez story (\"Death Constant Beyond Love\") to meet his narrative needs in the subplot of Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez.<ref name = \"Garc\u00eda Saucedo 94\">Warwick, '' Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine'', p. 94</ref>\n\nThe film was an international coproduction involving [[Mexico]], [[France]] and [[West Germany]]. It was shot in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] on locations in [[San Luis Potosi]], [[Veracruz]], [[Zacatecas]] and in studios in Mexico. It was entered into the [[1983 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1439/year/1983.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Er\u00e9ndira |accessdate=14 June 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and was selected as the Mexican entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[56th Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nEr\u00e9ndira, a teenaged girl, lives with her eccentric grandmother in a vast, gloomy house in a windswept desert region. Exploited by her grandmother, Er\u00e9ndira must work all day long doing the house chores, until she sleeps walk exhausted. The heartless grandmother lives in her own world, talking to herself and crying uncontrollably with sentimental French songs. One day Er\u00e9ndira is so tired from all the work that she falls sleep without extinguishing the candles. The curtains catch fire accidentally burning the house down to the foundation walls.\n\nHaving calculated the debt Er\u00e9ndira owes her for the destruction of her home and belongings, the grandmother decides the only way the girl will be able to repay such a vast amount is by prostituting herself. Er\u00e9ndira submits to her fate without a protest and the grandmother does not waste any time trading Er\u00e9ndira's virginity to a local merchant for 250 pesos and three days\u2019 provisions for their trip. When Er\u00e9ndira resists, the man slaps and rapes her.\n\nEr\u00e9ndira and her grandmother subsequently travel through the desert while the young girl sells her body to countless men \u2013 peasants, Indians, humble workers, soldiers and the smugglers that populate the region. The grandmother collects the money, makes all decisions, and pays the Indian servants. As the business prospers it achieves carnivalesque proportions: the two women are joined by hangers-on, vendors, musicians, and a mysterious photographer.\n\nOne day having had sex with an army of soldiers, Er\u00e9ndira falls sick and the line of men waiting outside her tent is dismissed. Then, Ulises, the young son of a smuggler traveling through the region, sneaks into the tent after the old woman has gone to sleep. Er\u00e9ndira finds him charming; she charges him for her services and teaches him how to make love. By the next morning Ulises has fallen in love with her.\n\nEn route from one town to the next, a group of monks take Er\u00e9ndira away from the grip of her grandmother sending her to their mission in the desert until she marries. Undaunted, the grandmother hires a Mexican peasant boy to marry Er\u00e9ndira and thus gets her granddaughter back in the same old rut. To undermine any further attempts by the priests to confiscate her money-making resource, the grandmother must obtain a letter from someone important testifying to her granddaughter's high moral character. The grandmother sends Er\u00e9ndira to Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez, a man dying of some mysterious disease. The crafty woman locks a chastity belt on Er\u00e9ndira, which the Senator discovers cannot be unlocked until he writes the letter.\n\nThe grandmother's business suffers a second setback when Ulises reappears and persuades Er\u00e9ndira to run off with him. His plan is to live off a fortune from oranges which contain diamonds smuggled by his Dutch father. The young couple heads for the border in a truck the boy has stolen from his father. Finally caught, Er\u00e9ndira watches from the halted truck as her lover suffers a whipping from his father. The grandmother, preventing a new escape attempt, chains her granddaughter to the bed. However, angry prostitutes, bereft of business because Er\u00e9ndira is in town, march to their competitor's tent and haul the young woman out of it over the old woman's curses.\n\nBy now the Grandmother is quite wealthy. She and Er\u00e9ndira live in a large tent beside the sea, furnished even more grandly than the lost desert home. The old woman plays her piano, bathes, and gives orders to her now hardened charge. Realizing that only her grandmother's death would free her, Er\u00e9ndira pushes Ulises to kill the old woman. Ulises first two attempts on her life by poisoning and an explosive are unsuccessful. Finally, goaded by Er\u00e9ndira, he picks up a kitchen knife and stabs the old woman in the back. With his grandmother's death, Er\u00e9ndira's palm suddenly acquires lines. She picks up her grandmother's vest of gold and runs off into the desert. Ulises is left alone crying.\"No voice on earth could stop me,\" Er\u00e9ndira tells us in a voice over as she disappears into the desert. \"And no trace of my misfortune was ever found.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Irene Papas]] as the grandmother\n* [[Cl\u00e1udia Ohana]] as Er\u00e9ndira\n* [[Michael Lonsdale]] as Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez\n* [[Oliver Wehe]] as Ulysses\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as the photographer\n* [[Blanca Guerra]] as Ulysses' mother\n* [[Ernesto G\u00f3mez Cruz]] as the grocer\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]] as Ulysses' father\n* [[Carlos Card\u00e1n]] as Smuggler\n* [[Humberto Elizondo]] as Blacaman\n* [[Jorge Feg\u00e1n]] as the commander\n* [[Francisco Mauri]] as the postman\n* Sergio Calder\u00f3n as the truck driver\n* [[Mart\u00edn Palomares]] as escort\n* [[Salvador Garcini]] as puppet-player\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 56th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Mexican submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Garc\u00eda Saucedo, Jaime. ''Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine''. panamericna Editorial. 2003. ISBN 958301025  -1\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0085501|Er\u00e9ndira}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erendira}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ruy Guerra]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1983 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Er\u00e9ndira\n| image          = Erendira.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ruy Guerra]]\n| producer       = Alain Queff\u00e9l\u00e9an<br>Regina Ziegler\n| writer         = [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n| starring       = [[Irene Papas]]<br>[[Cl\u00e1udia Ohana]]<br>Oliver Wehe<br>[[Michael Lonsdale]]\n| music          = Maurice Lecoeur\n| cinematography = [[Denys Clerval]]\n| editing        = Kenout Peltier\n| studio         = [[Les Films du Triangle]]<br>[[Films A2]]<br>[[Cin\u00e9 Qua Non]]<br>[[Atlas Saskia Film]]<br>[[Austra]]\n| distributor    = [[Miramax]]\n| released       = {{film date|1983|9|12|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = Mexico<br>France<br>West Germany\n| language       = Spanish\n}}\n\n'''''Er\u00e9ndira''''' is a 1983 [[drama film]] directed by [[Ruy Guerra]]. The film script was written by [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]. The original script actually preceded his [[novella]] ''[[The Incredible and Sad Tale of Innocent Er\u00e9ndira and Her Heartless Grandmother]]'' published in 1972.<ref name = \"Garc\u00eda Saucedo 93\">Warwick, ''Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine'', p. 93</ref> The characters of Er\u00e9ndira and her grandmother had already appeared briefly in his book ''[[One Hundred Years of Solitude]]'' (1967). Garcia Marquez' recreated the screenplay from memory (the original was lost) for Guerra's film.<ref>{{cite news\n | last =Canby\n | first = Vincent\n | title = ERENDIRA : A GIRL, A GRANDMOTHER AND A LIBERATOR\n | work =[[The New York Times]] \n | date = 1 October 1983\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1983/10/01/movies/erendira-a-girl-a-grandmother-and-a-liberator.html\n | accessdate = 14 July 2013 }}</ref> Guerra incorporated elements from another Garcia Marquez story (\"Death Constant Beyond Love\") to meet his narrative needs in the subplot of Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez.<ref name = \"Garc\u00eda Saucedo 94\">Warwick, '' Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine'', p. 94</ref>\n\nThe film was an international coproduction involving [[Mexico]], [[France]] and [[West Germany]]. It was shot in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] on locations in [[San Luis Potosi]], [[Veracruz]], [[Zacatecas]] and in studios in Mexico. It was entered into the [[1983 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1439/year/1983.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Er\u00e9ndira |accessdate=14 June 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and was selected as the Mexican entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[56th Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nEr\u00e9ndira, a teenaged girl, lives with her eccentric grandmother in a vast, gloomy house in a windswept desert region. Exploited by her grandmother, Er\u00e9ndira must work all day long doing the house chores, until she sleeps walk exhausted. The heartless grandmother lives in her own world, talking to herself and crying uncontrollably with sentimental French songs. One day Er\u00e9ndira is so tired from all the work that she falls sleep without extinguishing the candles. The curtains catch fire accidentally burning the house down to the foundation walls.\n\nHaving calculated the debt Er\u00e9ndira owes her for the destruction of her home and belongings, the grandmother decides the only way the girl will be able to repay such a vast amount is by prostituting herself. Er\u00e9ndira submits to her fate without a protest and the grandmother does not waste any time trading Er\u00e9ndira's virginity to a local merchant for 250 pesos and three days\u2019 provisions for their trip. When Er\u00e9ndira resists, the man slaps and rapes her.\n\nEr\u00e9ndira and her grandmother subsequently travel through the desert while the young girl sells her body to countless men \u2013 peasants, Indians, humble workers, soldiers and the smugglers that populate the region. The grandmother collects the money, makes all decisions, and pays the Indian servants. As the business prospers it achieves carnivalesque proportions: the two women are joined by hangers-on, vendors, musicians, and a mysterious photographer.\n\nOne day having had sex with an army of soldiers, Er\u00e9ndira falls sick and the line of men waiting outside her tent is dismissed. Then, Ulises, the young son of a smuggler traveling through the region, sneaks into the tent after the old woman has gone to sleep. Er\u00e9ndira finds him charming; she charges him for her services and teaches him how to make love. By the next morning Ulises has fallen in love with her.\n\nEn route from one town to the next, a group of monks take Er\u00e9ndira away from the grip of her grandmother sending her to their mission in the desert until she marries. Undaunted, the grandmother hires a Mexican peasant boy to marry Er\u00e9ndira and thus gets her granddaughter back in the same old rut. To undermine any further attempts by the priests to confiscate her money-making resource, the grandmother must obtain a letter from someone important testifying to her granddaughter's high moral character. The grandmother sends Er\u00e9ndira to Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez, a man dying of some mysterious disease. The crafty woman locks a chastity belt on Er\u00e9ndira, which the Senator discovers cannot be unlocked until he writes the letter.\n\nThe grandmother's business suffers a second setback when Ulises reappears and persuades Er\u00e9ndira to run off with him. His plan is to live off a fortune from oranges which contain diamonds smuggled by his Dutch father. The young couple heads for the border in a truck the boy has stolen from his father. Finally caught, Er\u00e9ndira watches from the halted truck as her lover suffers a whipping from his father. The grandmother, preventing a new escape attempt, chains her granddaughter to the bed. However, angry prostitutes, bereft of business because Er\u00e9ndira is in town, march to their competitor's tent and haul the young woman out of it over the old woman's curses.\n\nBy now the Grandmother is quite wealthy. She and Er\u00e9ndira live in a large tent beside the sea, furnished even more grandly than the lost desert home. The old woman plays her piano, bathes, and gives orders to her now hardened charge. Realizing that only her grandmother's death would free her, Er\u00e9ndira pushes Ulises to kill the old woman. Ulises first two attempts on her life by poisoning and an explosive are unsuccessful. Finally, goaded by Er\u00e9ndira, he picks up a kitchen knife and stabs the old woman in the back. With his grandmother's death, Er\u00e9ndira's palm suddenly acquires lines. She picks up her grandmother's vest of gold and runs off into the desert. Ulises is left alone crying.\"No voice on earth could stop me,\" Er\u00e9ndira tells us in a voice over as she disappears into the desert. \"And no trace of my misfortune was ever found.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Irene Papas]] as the grandmother\n* [[Cl\u00e1udia Ohana]] as Er\u00e9ndira\n* [[Michael Lonsdale]] as Senator On\u00e9simo Sanchez\n* [[Oliver Wehe]] as Ulysses\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as the photographer\n* [[Blanca Guerra]] as Ulysses' mother\n* [[Ernesto G\u00f3mez Cruz]] as the grocer\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]] as Ulysses' father\n* [[Carlos Card\u00e1n]] as Smuggler\n* [[Humberto Elizondo]] as Blacaman\n* [[Jorge Feg\u00e1n]] as the commander\n* [[Francisco Mauri]] as the postman\n* Sergio Calder\u00f3n as the truck driver\n* [[Mart\u00edn Palomares]] as escort\n* [[Salvador Garcini]] as puppet-player\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 56th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Mexican submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Garc\u00eda Saucedo, Jaime. ''Diccionario de literatura colombina en el cine''. panamericna Editorial. 2003. ISBN 958301025  -1\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0085501|Er\u00e9ndira}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erendira}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ruy Guerra]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Er%C3%A9ndira_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Hacienda HealthCare sexual abuse case", "text_new": "The '''Hacienda HealthCare sexual abuse case''' was a high-profile [[sexual abuse]] case involving a disabled woman in a [[persistent vegetative state]] who was allegedly raped many times and impregnated by a male nurse at the Hacienda HealthCare facility in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States. Although the investigation took place in 2019, the sexual abuse was long-term, and may have had gone unnoticed for years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Carter |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Incapacitated Arizona Woman Who Gave Birth After Rape Was Likely Pregnant Before, Family Says |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/7xgwk4/incapacitated-arizona-woman-who-gave-birth-after-rape-was-likely-pregnant-before-family-says |work=VICE News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe investigation garnered widespread international attention, and was covered by ''[[CNN]], [[USA Today]], [[US News]], The [[New York Times]]'', and even by major European and Asian media outlets.<ref>{{cite news |date=Jan 24, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse Nathan Sutherland arrested for rape of incapacitated woman who had baby at long-term care facility |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/2183392/arizona-nurse-nathan-sutherland-arrested-rape |work=South China Morning Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Geanous |first=Jacob |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Comatose woman who gave birth was \u2018raped and impregnated by care worker multiple times\u2019 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/23/comatose-woman-who-gave-birth-was-raped-and-impregnated-by-care-worker-multiple-times-9667582/ |work=Metro UK |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> It also prompted the State of [[Arizona]] to make drastic changes to the way their long-term care facilities are managed.<ref name=slate />\n\nOther well-known pregnancies involving sexually abused vegetative and comatose female patients have also been reported in [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1996, [[Massachusetts]] in 1998, and [[Argentina]] in 2015.<ref name=slate>{{cite news |last=Cauterucci |first=Christina |date=Jan 24, 2019 |title=A Horrifying Ethical Dilemma |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/01/hacienda-healthcare-incapacitated-woman-birth-vegetative-state.html |work=Slate |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> The highly publicized case points to a national problem of disabled women being disproportionately likely to suffer from [[sexual abuse]], at two to three times that of the general population.<ref>{{cite news |last=Filipovic |first=Jill |date=January 12, 2019 |title=Woman raped in vegetative state, and then giving birth, is an outrage |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/11/opinions/woman-raped-in-vegetative-state-giving-birth-violation-filipovic/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== The victim ==\nThe woman, originally from the [[San Carlos Apache Indian Reservation]], has been in a [[persistent vegetative state]] since 1992 at the age of 3. To protect her anonymity, she has not been named by news sources. Born in April 1989, the woman is [[intellectually disabled]] and non-verbal as a result of multiple childhood seizures she has had since she was 2 months old. Despite being in a vegetative state, the woman can experience pain and respond with facial gestures and some vocal sounds, such as crying when experiencing discomfort. She can also respond to auditory stimuli and has some limited ability to move her head, neck, and limbs. Also, the woman would often thrash her arms while hooked up to a ventilator.<ref name=12news /> \n\nThe woman had been cared for by Hacienda HealthCare, a non-profit entity receiving state funds, since childhood. She was reported to be 29 years old at the time the investigation took place in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 13, 2019 |title=Phoenix facility where woman in coma gave birth faced criminal inquiry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jan/13/woman-coma-birth-phoenix-facility-2016-investigation |work=The Guardian |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Sexual abuse ==\nThe victim was allegedly repeatedly raped, likely over many years, by Nathan Sutherland, who was 36 years old and married with four children at the time of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of woman in coma who gave birth |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/north-america/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-woman-in-vegetative-state-who-gave-birth/news-story/92aac41fef28fcf462726e1eb8d1362e |work=News Corp Australia |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> She had been in the care of Sutherland hundreds of times from 2012 to 2018. She has sustained injuries from repeated sexual assault, including vaginal trauma and gaping of the [[perineum]], and had experienced both vaginal and anal rape.<ref name=huffington>{{cite news |last=Vagianos |first=Alanna |date=2019-05-24 |title=Disabled Woman Raped At Hacienda HealthCare Was Likely Pregnant Before |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/hacienda-healthcare-rape-pregnant-arizona-lawsuit_n_5ce80e85e4b0a2f9f28e5982 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Sutherland was going through a divorce in late 2018, and his co-workers had noticed that he had been highly stressed at the time, but thought it was due to stress from the divorce.<ref name=12news>{{cite news |last=Concepcion |first=Mackenzie |date=June 13, 2019 |title=The woman with disabilities who gave birth after being raped at an Arizona nursing facility may have been pregnant before, new documents reveal |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/investigations/pray-for-me-police-report-shows-hacienda-rape-suspects-behavior-changed-before-victim-gave-birth/75-343d3958-c36e-486f-b4e6-a201f4eeeba1| work=NBC 12 News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pregnancy and birth ==\nThe victim became pregnant in 2018 while under full-time care at the Hacienda HealthCare facility. Remarkably, the woman's pregnancy had gone completely unnoticed by healthcare facility staff until she gave birth on December 29, 2018. Instead, facility staff had treated her for [[constipation]] and weight gain, and even reduced her caloric intake.<ref name=huffington />\n\nThe woman gave birth to a baby boy on the afternoon of December 29, 2018 without any major complications. However, immediately after facility staff had attended to the birth, the newborn baby was not breathing and had to be resuscitated. The newborn may grow up to have developmental problems, as the mother was on many different types of medications such as [[phenobarbital]] and had not received any pregnancy-related care.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news |date=January 16, 2019 |title=Son of sexually assaulted comatose woman is the second victim: Today's talker |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/01/16/son-comatose-woman-hacienda-healthcare-second-victim-talker/2592029002/ |work=USA Today |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nOn December 29, Hacienda HealthCare staff promptly called 911 when they discovered that the woman had given birth. An investigation was promptly launched, with DNA samples taken from all male nurses at the Hacienda HealthCare facility. On January 22, 2019, the DNA results of the newborn baby were matched with Nathan Sutherland's DNA, who was then arrested that same day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wootson Jr. |first=Cleve R. |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse charged with sexual assault after woman in incapacitated state gave birth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/23/nurse-charged-with-sexual-assault-after-incapacitated-woman-gave-birth-health-care-facility/ |work=Washington Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Sutherland then voluntarily gave up his nursing license on January 24, following his arrest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bean |first=Mackenzie |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor calls for removal of Hacienda HealthCare's board amid sexual assault probe |url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/hospital-management-administration/arizona-governor-calls-for-removal-of-hacienda-healthcare-s-board.html |work=Becker's Hospital Review |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]]-based gynecologist [[Gregory Marchand]], who had conducted an extensive medical investigation of the case and provided post-natal care, there was \"no doubt\" that the victim had experienced pain,<ref>{{cite news |date=2019 |title=Doctor Says Woman Who Gave Birth in Vegetative State Likely Felt Pain |url=https://www.insideedition.com/media/videos/doctor-says-woman-who-gave-birth-vegetative-state-likely-felt-pain-49839 |work=Inside Edition |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pate |first=Kelli |date=January 6, 2019 |title=Woman In A Vegetative State For 14 Years Gives Birth After Being Assaulted |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/01/220896/phoenix-coma-rape-woman-gives-birth |work=Refinery29 |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> and that the lack of monitoring during the woman's pregnancy and childbirth could have easily resulted in [[fetal death]].<ref>{{cite news |date=2019 |title=Woman In Coma for 14 years Gives Birth To Baby Boy |url=https://denvertelegram.com/woman-in-coma-for-14-years-gives-birth-to-baby-boy/ |work=The Denver Telegram |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=January 10, 2019 |title=Police seek DNA in investigation into comatose woman\u2019s birth |url=https://www.today.com/video/police-seek-dna-in-investigation-into-comatose-woman-s-birth-1423268419722 |work=Today |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> However, Marchand believes that it is very difficult to determine whether the victim had in fact been pregnant multiple times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Planalp |first=Carissa |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Gynecologist: 'Very difficult' to determine if Hacienda HealthCare rape victim had previous pregnancy  |url=https://www.azfamily.com/news/investigations/hacienda_healthcare/gynecologist-very-difficult-to-determine-if-hacienda-healthcare-rape-victim/article_aef42d0e-7db8-11e9-b352-23eb1ca37259.html |work=AZ Family |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nHacienda HealthCare's CEO Bill Timmons resigned on January 7, with Arizona state governor [[Doug Ducey]] also calling for the resignation of Hacienda HealthCare's board of directors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keith |first=Allen |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor 'sickened' by impregnation of disabled woman, says health care facility board should quit |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/25/us/hacienda-healthcare-leadership-criticized/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor urges new leaders at facility after rape |url=https://federalnewsnetwork.com/business-news/2019/01/arizona-governor-urges-new-leaders-at-facility-after-rape/ |work=Federal News Network |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> The Hacienda HealthCare facility was closed soon afterwards in February 2019, which had 37 residents in its care at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevens |first=Matt |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Arizona Nursing Center Where Woman in Vegetative State Was Raped Will Close |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/us/hacienda-healthcare-phoenix-closing.html |work=New York Times |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=June 16, 2019 |title=Arizona facility where incapacitated woman gave birth faces more trouble after maggots are found on patient |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/arizona-facility-where-incapacitated-woman-gave-birth-faces-more-trouble-n1017946 |work=NBC News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> One physician at the facility resigned, while another was suspended.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fedschun |first=Travis |date=January 23, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of woman in vegetative state who gave birth at care facility |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-woman-in-vegetative-state-who-gave-birth-at-care-facility |work=FOX News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Later, investigators also found maggots on a male patient at the Hacienda HealthCare facility, prompting the [[Arizona Department of Health Services]] to revoke the healthcare facility's license due to [[negligence]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Holle |first=Silverman |date=June 18, 2019 |title=The healthcare facility where a severely disabled woman gave birth may close after maggots were found on another resident |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/18/us/arizona-healthcare-facility-closure/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stockler |first=Asher |date=June 15, 2019 |title=Arizona Health Officials Want to Revoke License of Facility That Let Maggots Collect on Patient's Wound, Twice |url=https://www.newsweek.com/arizona-health-officials-want-revoke-license-facility-that-let-maggots-collect-patients-wound-1444188 |work=Newsweek |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Salo |first=Jackie |date=June 17, 2019 |title=Maggots found on patient at same Arizona facility where disabled woman allegedly raped  |url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/17/maggots-found-on-patient-at-same-arizona-facility-where-disabled-woman-allegedly-raped/ |work=NY Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> However, Hacienda HealthCare regained its license on May 1, with Perry Petrilli appointed as acting CEO.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 1, 2019 |title=Arizona Licenses Center Where Incapacitated Woman Was Raped |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/arizona/articles/2019-05-01/arizona-grants-license-for-care-facility-where-rape-occurred |work=US News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the investigation, the State of Arizona has vowed to improve oversight of all care facilities in the state.<ref name=slate />\n\n== Lawsuit and trial ==\nThe victim's family filed a $45 million lawsuit against the State of Arizona, which accused the state of \"[[gross negligence]],\" and that it had \"cultivated circumstances\" which allowed for the lack of monitoring in long-term care facilities. The lawsuit sought a $25 million settlement for the victim, a $10 million settlement for the victim's father, and an additional $10 for her mother.<ref>{{cite news |last=Romo |first=Vanessa |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Disabled Woman Who Gave Birth At Care Facility May Have Been Impregnated Before |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/23/726207219/disabled-woman-who-gave-birth-at-care-facility-may-have-been-impregnated-before |work=NPR |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe lawsuit also claimed that the family had requested for female nurses to take care of their daughter since 2002 when staff claimed that their daughter had been \"touched inappropriately,\" but this request had never been carried out by the facility.<ref name=12news /><ref>{{cite news |last=Collman |first=Ashley |date=May 24, 2019 |title=The woman with disabilities who gave birth after being raped at an Arizona nursing facility may have been pregnant before, new documents reveal |url=https://www.insider.com/hacienda-healthcare-patient-may-have-been-pregnant-before-2019-5 |work=Insider |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNathan Sutherland, defended by attorney David Gregan,<ref>{{cite news |last=Tang |first=Terry |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of incapacitated Arizona woman who gave birth at facility |url=https://tucson.com/news/state-and-regional/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-incapacitated-arizona-woman-who-gave/article_7f10d23e-1f32-11e9-94b6-638ca39b052d.html |work=tucson.com |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> pleaded not guilty on February 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=David |first=Schwatz |date=February 5, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse pleads not guilty to raping disabled woman who gave birth |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-arizona-crime/arizona-nurse-pleads-not-guilty-to-raping-disabled-woman-who-gave-birth-idUSKCN1PU13S |work=Reuters |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mindock |first=Clark |date=February 6, 2019 |title=Nathan Sutherland: Nurse pleads not guilty to raping severely disabled woman in Arizona care home |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nathan-sutherland-arizona-nurse-rape-vegetative-state-pregnant-hacienda-healthcare-a8765011.html |work=Independent UK |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=Feb 6, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse pleads not guilty to raping disabled woman who gave birth |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/arizona-nurse-pleads-not-guilty-to-raping-disabled-woman-who-gave-birth |work=Straits Times |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Sexual abuse and intellectual disability]]\n*[[Disability abuse]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{abuse}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Rapes in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Hacienda HealthCare sexual abuse case''' was a high-profile [[sexual abuse]] case involving a disabled woman in a [[persistent vegetative state]] who was allegedly raped many times and impregnated by a male nurse at the Hacienda HealthCare facility in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States. Although the investigation took place in 2019, the sexual abuse was long-term, and may have had gone unnoticed for years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Carter |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Incapacitated Arizona Woman Who Gave Birth After Rape Was Likely Pregnant Before, Family Says |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/7xgwk4/incapacitated-arizona-woman-who-gave-birth-after-rape-was-likely-pregnant-before-family-says |work=VICE News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe investigation garnered widespread international attention, and was covered by ''[[CNN]], [[USA Today]], [[US News]], The [[New York Times]]'', and even by major European and Asian media outlets.<ref>{{cite news |date=Jan 24, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse Nathan Sutherland arrested for rape of incapacitated woman who had baby at long-term care facility |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/2183392/arizona-nurse-nathan-sutherland-arrested-rape |work=South China Morning Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Geanous |first=Jacob |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Comatose woman who gave birth was \u2018raped and impregnated by care worker multiple times\u2019 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/23/comatose-woman-who-gave-birth-was-raped-and-impregnated-by-care-worker-multiple-times-9667582/ |work=Metro UK |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> It also prompted the State of [[Arizona]] to make drastic changes to the way their long-term care facilities are managed.<ref name=slate />\n\nOther well-known pregnancies involving sexually abused vegetative and comatose female patients have also been reported in [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1996, [[Massachusetts]] in 1998, and [[Argentina]] in 2015.<ref name=slate>{{cite news |last=Cauterucci |first=Christina |date=Jan 24, 2019 |title=A Horrifying Ethical Dilemma |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/01/hacienda-healthcare-incapacitated-woman-birth-vegetative-state.html |work=Slate |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> The highly publicized case points to a national problem of disabled women being disproportionately likely to suffer from [[sexual abuse]], at two to three times that of the general population.<ref>{{cite news |last=Filipovic |first=Jill |date=January 12, 2019 |title=Woman raped in vegetative state, and then giving birth, is an outrage |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/11/opinions/woman-raped-in-vegetative-state-giving-birth-violation-filipovic/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== The victim ==\nThe woman, originally from the [[San Carlos Apache Indian Reservation]], has been in a [[persistent vegetative state]] since 1992 at the age of 3. To protect her anonymity, she has not been named by news sources. Born in April 1989, the woman is [[intellectually disabled]] and non-verbal as a result of multiple childhood seizures she has had since she was 2 months old. Despite being in a vegetative state, the woman can experience pain and respond with facial gestures and some vocal sounds, such as crying when experiencing discomfort. She can also respond to auditory stimuli and has some limited ability to move her head, neck, and limbs. Also, the woman would often thrash her arms while hooked up to a ventilator.<ref name=12news /> \n\nThe woman had been cared for by Hacienda HealthCare, a non-profit entity receiving state funds, since childhood. She was reported to be 29 years old at the time the investigation took place in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 13, 2019 |title=Phoenix facility where woman in coma gave birth faced criminal inquiry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jan/13/woman-coma-birth-phoenix-facility-2016-investigation |work=The Guardian |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Sexual abuse ==\nThe victim was allegedly repeatedly raped, likely over many years, by Nathan Sutherland, who was 36 years old and married with four children at the time of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of woman in coma who gave birth |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/north-america/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-woman-in-vegetative-state-who-gave-birth/news-story/92aac41fef28fcf462726e1eb8d1362e |work=News Corp Australia |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> She had been in the care of Sutherland hundreds of times from 2012 to 2018. She has sustained injuries from repeated sexual assault, including vaginal trauma and gaping of the [[perineum]], and had experienced both vaginal and anal rape.<ref name=huffington>{{cite news |last=Vagianos |first=Alanna |date=2019-05-24 |title=Disabled Woman Raped At Hacienda HealthCare Was Likely Pregnant Before |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/hacienda-healthcare-rape-pregnant-arizona-lawsuit_n_5ce80e85e4b0a2f9f28e5982 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Sutherland was going through a divorce in late 2018, and his co-workers had noticed that he had been highly stressed at the time, but thought it was due to stress from the divorce.<ref name=12news>{{cite news |last=Concepcion |first=Mackenzie |date=June 13, 2019 |title=The woman with disabilities who gave birth after being raped at an Arizona nursing facility may have been pregnant before, new documents reveal |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/investigations/pray-for-me-police-report-shows-hacienda-rape-suspects-behavior-changed-before-victim-gave-birth/75-343d3958-c36e-486f-b4e6-a201f4eeeba1| work=NBC 12 News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pregnancy and birth ==\nThe victim became pregnant in 2018 while under full-time care at the Hacienda HealthCare facility. Remarkably, the woman's pregnancy had gone completely unnoticed by healthcare facility staff until she gave birth on December 29, 2018. Instead, facility staff had treated her for [[constipation]] and weight gain, and even reduced her caloric intake.<ref name=huffington />\n\nThe woman gave birth to a baby boy on the afternoon of December 29, 2018 without any major complications. However, immediately after facility staff had attended to the birth, the newborn baby was not breathing and had to be resuscitated. The newborn may grow up to have developmental problems, as the mother was on many different types of medications such as [[phenobarbital]] and had not received any pregnancy-related care.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news |date=January 16, 2019 |title=Son of sexually assaulted comatose woman is the second victim: Today's talker |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/01/16/son-comatose-woman-hacienda-healthcare-second-victim-talker/2592029002/ |work=USA Today |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nOn December 29, Hacienda HealthCare staff promptly called 911 when they discovered that the woman had given birth. An investigation was promptly launched, with DNA samples taken from all male nurses at the Hacienda HealthCare facility. On January 22, 2019, the DNA results of the newborn baby were matched with Nathan Sutherland's DNA, who was then arrested that same day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wootson Jr. |first=Cleve R. |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse charged with sexual assault after woman in incapacitated state gave birth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/23/nurse-charged-with-sexual-assault-after-incapacitated-woman-gave-birth-health-care-facility/ |work=Washington Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Sutherland then voluntarily gave up his nursing license on January 24, following his arrest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bean |first=Mackenzie |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor calls for removal of Hacienda HealthCare's board amid sexual assault probe |url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/hospital-management-administration/arizona-governor-calls-for-removal-of-hacienda-healthcare-s-board.html |work=Becker's Hospital Review |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]]-based gynecologist Gregory Marchand, who had conducted an extensive medical investigation of the case and provided post-natal care, there was \"no doubt\" that the victim had experienced pain,<ref>{{cite news |date=2019 |title=Doctor Says Woman Who Gave Birth in Vegetative State Likely Felt Pain |url=https://www.insideedition.com/media/videos/doctor-says-woman-who-gave-birth-vegetative-state-likely-felt-pain-49839 |work=Inside Edition |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pate |first=Kelli |date=January 6, 2019 |title=Woman In A Vegetative State For 14 Years Gives Birth After Being Assaulted |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/01/220896/phoenix-coma-rape-woman-gives-birth |work=Refinery29 |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> and that the lack of monitoring during the woman's pregnancy and childbirth could have easily resulted in [[fetal death]].<ref>{{cite news |date=2019 |title=Woman In Coma for 14 years Gives Birth To Baby Boy |url=https://denvertelegram.com/woman-in-coma-for-14-years-gives-birth-to-baby-boy/ |work=The Denver Telegram |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=January 10, 2019 |title=Police seek DNA in investigation into comatose woman\u2019s birth |url=https://www.today.com/video/police-seek-dna-in-investigation-into-comatose-woman-s-birth-1423268419722 |work=Today |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> However, Marchand believes that it is very difficult to determine whether the victim had in fact been pregnant multiple times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Planalp |first=Carissa |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Gynecologist: 'Very difficult' to determine if Hacienda HealthCare rape victim had previous pregnancy  |url=https://www.azfamily.com/news/investigations/hacienda_healthcare/gynecologist-very-difficult-to-determine-if-hacienda-healthcare-rape-victim/article_aef42d0e-7db8-11e9-b352-23eb1ca37259.html |work=AZ Family |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nHacienda HealthCare's CEO Bill Timmons resigned on January 7, with Arizona state governor [[Doug Ducey]] also calling for the resignation of Hacienda HealthCare's board of directors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keith |first=Allen |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor 'sickened' by impregnation of disabled woman, says health care facility board should quit |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/25/us/hacienda-healthcare-leadership-criticized/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Arizona governor urges new leaders at facility after rape |url=https://federalnewsnetwork.com/business-news/2019/01/arizona-governor-urges-new-leaders-at-facility-after-rape/ |work=Federal News Network |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> The Hacienda HealthCare facility was closed soon afterwards in February 2019, which had 37 residents in its care at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevens |first=Matt |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Arizona Nursing Center Where Woman in Vegetative State Was Raped Will Close |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/us/hacienda-healthcare-phoenix-closing.html |work=New York Times |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=June 16, 2019 |title=Arizona facility where incapacitated woman gave birth faces more trouble after maggots are found on patient |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/arizona-facility-where-incapacitated-woman-gave-birth-faces-more-trouble-n1017946 |work=NBC News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> One physician at the facility resigned, while another was suspended.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fedschun |first=Travis |date=January 23, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of woman in vegetative state who gave birth at care facility |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-woman-in-vegetative-state-who-gave-birth-at-care-facility |work=FOX News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Later, investigators also found maggots on a male patient at the Hacienda HealthCare facility, prompting the [[Arizona Department of Health Services]] to revoke the healthcare facility's license due to [[negligence]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Holle |first=Silverman |date=June 18, 2019 |title=The healthcare facility where a severely disabled woman gave birth may close after maggots were found on another resident |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/18/us/arizona-healthcare-facility-closure/index.html |work=CNN |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stockler |first=Asher |date=June 15, 2019 |title=Arizona Health Officials Want to Revoke License of Facility That Let Maggots Collect on Patient's Wound, Twice |url=https://www.newsweek.com/arizona-health-officials-want-revoke-license-facility-that-let-maggots-collect-patients-wound-1444188 |work=Newsweek |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Salo |first=Jackie |date=June 17, 2019 |title=Maggots found on patient at same Arizona facility where disabled woman allegedly raped  |url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/17/maggots-found-on-patient-at-same-arizona-facility-where-disabled-woman-allegedly-raped/ |work=NY Post |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> However, Hacienda HealthCare regained its license on May 1, with Perry Petrilli appointed as acting CEO.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 1, 2019 |title=Arizona Licenses Center Where Incapacitated Woman Was Raped |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/arizona/articles/2019-05-01/arizona-grants-license-for-care-facility-where-rape-occurred |work=US News |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the investigation, the State of Arizona has vowed to improve oversight of all care facilities in the state.<ref name=slate />\n\n== Lawsuit and trial ==\nThe victim's family filed a $45 million lawsuit against the State of Arizona, which accused the state of \"[[gross negligence]],\" and that it had \"cultivated circumstances\" which allowed for the lack of monitoring in long-term care facilities. The lawsuit sought a $25 million settlement for the victim, a $10 million settlement for the victim's father, and an additional $10 for her mother.<ref>{{cite news |last=Romo |first=Vanessa |date=May 23, 2019 |title=Disabled Woman Who Gave Birth At Care Facility May Have Been Impregnated Before |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/23/726207219/disabled-woman-who-gave-birth-at-care-facility-may-have-been-impregnated-before |work=NPR |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe lawsuit also claimed that the family had requested for female nurses to take care of their daughter since 2002 when staff claimed that their daughter had been \"touched inappropriately,\" but this request had never been carried out by the facility.<ref name=12news /><ref>{{cite news |last=Collman |first=Ashley |date=May 24, 2019 |title=The woman with disabilities who gave birth after being raped at an Arizona nursing facility may have been pregnant before, new documents reveal |url=https://www.insider.com/hacienda-healthcare-patient-may-have-been-pregnant-before-2019-5 |work=Insider |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNathan Sutherland, defended by attorney David Gregan,<ref>{{cite news |last=Tang |first=Terry |date=January 24, 2019 |title=Nurse arrested in rape of incapacitated Arizona woman who gave birth at facility |url=https://tucson.com/news/state-and-regional/nurse-arrested-in-rape-of-incapacitated-arizona-woman-who-gave/article_7f10d23e-1f32-11e9-94b6-638ca39b052d.html |work=tucson.com |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> pleaded not guilty on February 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=David |first=Schwatz |date=February 5, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse pleads not guilty to raping disabled woman who gave birth |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-arizona-crime/arizona-nurse-pleads-not-guilty-to-raping-disabled-woman-who-gave-birth-idUSKCN1PU13S |work=Reuters |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mindock |first=Clark |date=February 6, 2019 |title=Nathan Sutherland: Nurse pleads not guilty to raping severely disabled woman in Arizona care home |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nathan-sutherland-arizona-nurse-rape-vegetative-state-pregnant-hacienda-healthcare-a8765011.html |work=Independent UK |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=Feb 6, 2019 |title=Arizona nurse pleads not guilty to raping disabled woman who gave birth |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/arizona-nurse-pleads-not-guilty-to-raping-disabled-woman-who-gave-birth |work=Straits Times |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Sexual abuse and intellectual disability]]\n*[[Disability abuse]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{abuse}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Rapes in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Nilanda2019", "label": "safe", "comment": "linked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hacienda_HealthCare_sexual_abuse_case"}
